Using the same data set (credit_card_data.txt or credit_card_data-headers.txt) as in Question 2.2, use the ksvm or kknn function to find a good classifier: (a) using cross-validation (do this for the k-nearest-neighbors model; SVM is optional); and (b) splitting the data into training, validation, and test data sets (pick either KNN or SVM; the other is optional).

K-fold cross validation. K=10. Split data into K equal parts

k<-10
dsplits <- split(as.data.frame(learning[-1:-(mlearning %% k),]), rep(1:k, each = round(mlearning / k)))

# get the indexes for the dsplits list to create the combinations of training (tdata) and validation (vdata) datasets

numbers <- c(1:k)
dComb<-combinations(k,k-1,numbers[1:k])
maxSum<-sum(seq(1:k))

# validation data index
vIndex<- maxSum-rowSums(dComb)

Function to train model based on the algorithm

trainAndPredict <- function(tData,vData,modelName,knnVal,cval){
  if(modelName == "ksvm"){
    model <- NULL
    model <- ksvm(x=tData[,1:10],y=tData[,11], type="C-svc",  kernel="vanilladot", C=cval, scaled=TRUE) 
    a <- colSums(model@xmatrix[[1]] * model@coef[[1]])
    a0 <- -model@b
    pred <- predict(model,vData[, 1:10])
    acc = sum(pred == vData[,11]) / nrow(vData)
    return (acc)
  }
  else if(modelName == "knn"){
  
   predicted <- rep(0,(nrow(vData)))
    
      m = dim(vData)[1]
   
      kknnmodel_2 <-NULL
      kknnmodel_2 <- kknn(R1~.,tData,vData,k=knnVal, kernel="triangular", scale=TRUE) 
      fit <- fitted(kknnmodel_2)
      predicted = fit
      acc = sum(predicted == vData[,11])/m
    
     return (acc)
    
  }
    
    return (0)
}

trainLoop <- function(val) {
  results <- list()
  accKsvm<- array()
  for (i in 1:k) {
   #training data
    tData<-as.matrix(rbindlist(dsplits[-vIndex[i]]))
   #validation data
    vData<-as.matrix(rbindlist(dsplits[vIndex[i]]))
    # accuracy array
    accKsvm[i]=trainAndPredict(tData,vData,"ksvm",0,cval=val)
    }
  
  return(data.table(Cval=val,avgAccuracy=sum(accKsvm)/length(accKsvm)))
  
  }

Lets view the relation of each variable to the overall dataset

pairs(iris[,1:4], pch = 19, lower.panel = NULL)

Lets train models on the following combinations which as per the above graph may produce distinct clusters

  1. Sepal.Width, Petal.Width
  2. Sepal.Length, Petal.Width
  3. Sepal.Length, Petal.length
  4. Petal.Length, Petal.Width

Lets Plot the elbow graph to Figure out the optimal value of K for the combinations. Recall that the elbow graph is a plot of sum of squared errors within a group and number of groups

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:data.table':
## 
##     between, first, last
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
trainModels <- function(data,label) {
  num_of_clusters <-20
plot_data<- array()
between_cluster<-array()
for (i in 1:num_of_clusters){
    cl <- kmeans(data,i,nstart = 20)
    plot_data[i] <- (cl$tot.withinss)
}

plot(1:num_of_clusters, plot_data, type="o" ,xlab="Number of clusters",
                     ylab="Sum of squares within a cluster", main=label)

}

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
trainModels(select(iris,Sepal.Length, Petal.Width),"Sepal Length, Petal Width")
trainModels(select(iris, Sepal.Length,Petal.Length),"Sepal.Length,Petal.Length")
trainModels(select(iris, Sepal.Width, Petal.Width),"Sepal.Width, Petal.Width")
trainModels(select(iris, Petal.Length, Petal.Width),"Petal.Length, Petal.Width")

It seems Petal.Length and Petal.Width are a good choise of attributes due to the quick convergence of the elbow graph, above, at K=3, the elbow flattens out and beyond that has no significance change.

Train a K-means model with K=3

cl <- kmeans(select(iris,Petal.Length, Petal.Width),3,nstart = 20)
